lia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name, either from the district of Arden in Warwickshire or from Arden in Bredbury (Cheshire). The first placename is thought to be derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘high place’, cognate with <i>Ardennes</i>, the name of a forested region on the borders between northeastern France and eastern Belgium. The second derives from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>worthign</i> ‘enclosed settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Harden","meanings":["English: variant of   Arden   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>.","English: habitational name, either from Haredene Wood in East Tisbury (Wiltshire), or from Haredon (in Ugborough, Devon). The first placename probably derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. The second is from Old English <i>hara</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hare hill’.","English: variant of   Harding  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1354686,"age":92,"year":"1469","julianDay":2257602,"description":"The marriage of Prince Ferdinand of Aragon and Princess Isabella of Castille.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1354687,"age":97,"year":"1474","julianDay":2259428,"description":"Isabella became Queen of Castile.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Arden was